    "content": "1st: C — 2nd: B — 3rd: A — Reason: This collection needs a Translator's Preface more than it needs a Foreword. The translation decisions are unusually extensive and philosophically consequential — why 境 is transliterated, why \"phenomenal X\" is preserved, why Essay 2 is untouched, why the working-draft quality is kept, why the five registers matter. A reader who enters without this orientation will misread the translation as clumsy where it is deliberate. A Foreword by an outside scholar adds legitimacy but cannot do this work — the scholar would need to understand the translation decisions, not just the philosophy. If we do get a Foreword (option B), it should come from someone who can speak to the cross-traditional significance (the convergence with Husserl, Nagarjuna, Wittgenstein, Kant) without reducing the author to \"influenced by.\" But the Translator's Preface is non-negotiable; the Foreword is nice to have."
